1
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:20,000
<i>Subtitled by Subscene (Divxstation)</i>
2
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:28,000
SUPERMAN RETURNS (2006)

3
00:01:08,120 --> 00:01:12,480
<i>You will travel far, my little Kal-El.</i>

4
00:01:13,040 --> 00:01:15,120
<i>But we will never leave you...</i>

5
00:01:15,520 --> 00:01:18,080
<i>...even in the face of our deaths.</i>

6
00:01:19,280 --> 00:01:21,720
<i>You will make my strength your own.</i>

7
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:26,160
<i>You will see my life through your eyes...</i>

8
00:01:27,080 --> 00:01:29,720
<i>...as your life will be seen through mine.</i>

9
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:36,920
<i>The son becomes the father,
and the father the son.</i>

10
00:04:54,080 --> 00:04:56,520
<i>In spite of your past...</i>

11
00:04:58,680 --> 00:05:01,280
...I know you're a good man.

12
00:05:02,720 --> 00:05:04,440
And all good men...

13
00:05:04,960 --> 00:05:07,360
...deserve a second chance.

14
00:05:15,080 --> 00:05:18,040
From the moment
I received your first letter...

15
00:05:18,200 --> 00:05:20,920
...I knew you were not like the rest.

16
00:05:22,400 --> 00:05:26,160
You came from nothing...

17
00:05:26,760 --> 00:05:29,480
...and you worked so hard
to get where you are.

18
00:05:30,400 --> 00:05:33,120
You might have made a few mistakes.

19
00:05:33,480 --> 00:05:36,160
- Gertrude, for God's sake!
- Damn it, Gertrude, let us in now!

20
00:05:36,520 --> 00:05:41,720
You said that if I helped you
get out of prison...

21
00:05:42,800 --> 00:05:45,240
...you'd take care of me.

22
00:05:46,200 --> 00:05:48,280
And you have.

23
00:05:49,600 --> 00:05:53,640
You've shown me pleasures
that I've never known.

24
00:05:55,280 --> 00:05:57,400
That's why you deserve...

25
00:05:57,560 --> 00:05:59,400
...everything.

26
00:06:02,720 --> 00:06:04,160
I love you...

27
00:06:04,680 --> 00:06:06,640
...Lex Luthor.

28
00:06:22,200 --> 00:06:24,600
Gertrude, let us in. He's a crook.

29
00:06:24,760 --> 00:06:26,720
He doesn't love you, Gertrude!

30
00:06:26,880 --> 00:06:28,200
He's a monster! Gertrude!

31
00:06:45,120 --> 00:06:47,240
- You can keep that.
- Oh, God.

32
00:06:47,400 --> 00:06:48,640
The rest is mine.

33
00:06:54,800 --> 00:06:56,440
We're done.

34
00:07:24,760 --> 00:07:26,840
Bye, Martha.

35
00:09:57,240 --> 00:09:59,240
Oh, Clark.

36
00:10:02,040 --> 00:10:04,760
Oh, my boy.

37
00:10:50,840 --> 00:10:53,400
Will you get that thing out of my face!

38
00:10:59,720 --> 00:11:01,720
Lex, your friends give me the creeps.

39
00:11:01,880 --> 00:11:03,680
Prison is a creepy place, Kitty.

40
00:11:03,840 --> 00:11:06,200
One needs to make creepy friends
in order to survive.

41
00:11:06,360 --> 00:11:08,760
Even a man with my vast talents
is worth less inside...

42
00:11:08,920 --> 00:11:12,640
...than a carton of cigarettes and
a sharp piece of metal in your pocket.

43
00:11:16,160 --> 00:11:19,200
Do you know the story of Prometheus?
No, of course you don't.

44
00:11:19,360 --> 00:11:23,240
Prometheus was a god who stole
the power of fire from the other gods...

45
00:11:23,400 --> 00:11:25,080
...and gave control of it to mortals.

46
00:11:25,240 --> 00:11:27,800
In essence, he gave us technology.
He gave us power.

47
00:11:27,960 --> 00:11:31,360
So we're stealing fire? In the Arctic.

48
00:11:31,520 --> 00:11:35,000
Actually, sort of. You see, whoever
controls technology controls the world.

49
00:11:35,160 --> 00:11:37,720
The Roman Empire ruled the world
because they built roads.

50
00:11:37,880 --> 00:11:40,720
The British Empire ruled the world
because they built ships.

51
00:11:40,880 --> 00:11:44,240
America, the atom bomb,
and so on and so forth.

52
00:11:44,400 --> 00:11:46,000
I just want what Prometheus wanted.

53
00:11:46,360 --> 00:11:49,840
Sounds great, Lex, but you're not a god.

54
00:11:52,760 --> 00:11:55,680
Gods are selfish beings
who fly around in little red capes...

55
00:11:55,840 --> 00:11:58,040
...and don't share their power
with mankind.

56
00:11:58,200 --> 00:11:59,760
Hey, boss.

57
00:12:00,360 --> 00:12:01,920
We found something.

58
00:12:06,640 --> 00:12:09,240
No, I don't wanna be a god.

59
00:12:09,400 --> 00:12:12,360
I just wanna bring fire to the people.

60
00:12:13,400 --> 00:12:16,920
And I want my cut.

61
00:12:57,880 --> 00:13:00,120
Was this his house?

62
00:13:00,880 --> 00:13:03,360
You might think so. Most would.

63
00:13:03,520 --> 00:13:06,440
This is more of a monument
to a long dead...

64
00:13:06,600 --> 00:13:09,080
...and extremely powerful civilization.

65
00:13:09,240 --> 00:13:11,800
This is where he learned who he was.

66
00:13:12,280 --> 00:13:14,840
This is where he came for guidance.

67
00:13:25,320 --> 00:13:27,280
Possibilities.

68
00:13:27,440 --> 00:13:31,360
Endless possibilities.

69
00:14:14,480 --> 00:14:17,360
You act like you've been here before.

70
00:14:42,360 --> 00:14:44,120
<i>My son...</i>

71
00:14:46,520 --> 00:14:48,840
<i>...you do not remember me.</i>

72
00:14:49,760 --> 00:14:51,800
<i>I am Jor-El.</i>

73
00:14:52,200 --> 00:14:54,200
<i>I'm your father.</i>

74
00:14:54,360 --> 00:14:58,280
<i>By now, I will have been dead
many thousands of your years.</i>

75
00:14:58,440 --> 00:15:01,800
<i>- He thinks I'm his son.
- You are the only survivor of Krypton.</i>

76
00:15:02,400 --> 00:15:07,400
<i>Embedded in the crystals before you is
the total accumulation of all literature...</i>

77
00:15:07,560 --> 00:15:10,320
<i>...and scientific fact
from dozens of other worlds...</i>

78
00:15:10,480 --> 00:15:13,760
<i>...spanning the 28 known galaxies.</i>

79
00:15:14,240 --> 00:15:16,600
<i>There are questions to be asked.</i>

80
00:15:17,200 --> 00:15:18,800
<i>Here in this...</i>

81
00:15:18,960 --> 00:15:21,360
<i>This Fortress of Solitude...</i>

82
00:15:21,880 --> 00:15:25,240
<i>...we shall try to find
the answers together.</i>

83
00:15:25,400 --> 00:15:26,840
Can he see us?

84
00:15:27,560 --> 00:15:29,120
No, he's dead.

85
00:15:30,280 --> 00:15:31,560
<i>So, my son...</i>

86
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:36,760
<i>...Kal-El...</i>

87
00:15:40,120 --> 00:15:42,080
<i>...speak.</i>

88
00:15:43,680 --> 00:15:45,560
Tell me everything...

89
00:15:45,720 --> 00:15:48,240
...starting with crystals.

90
00:18:37,840 --> 00:18:39,240
Hey, boy.

91
00:19:04,280 --> 00:19:06,200
<i>- on Tuesday, between support...</i>

92
00:19:06,360 --> 00:19:08,600
<i>- hindered the firefighting efforts
for all those...</i>

93
00:19:08,760 --> 00:19:13,240
<i>Police have finally arrived and it's
still complete mayhem down here.</i>

94
00:19:14,560 --> 00:19:16,840
<i>Fighting broke out in the
southernmost region...</i>

95
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:19,320
<i>...with border fire
and small-arms attacks prevalent.</i>

96
00:19:19,480 --> 00:19:21,160
Don't worry, I buried it this morning.

97
00:19:21,320 --> 00:19:24,280
<i>- it was futile trying to force him
to testify before a grand jury.</i>

98
00:19:24,440 --> 00:19:25,880
Mom?

99
00:19:27,240 --> 00:19:29,160
Five years.

100
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:34,240
If your father was alive,
he never would have let you go.

101
00:19:34,920 --> 00:19:36,440
I almost gave up hope.

102
00:19:36,600 --> 00:19:39,720
I just thought
I would never see you again.

103
00:19:40,440 --> 00:19:42,920
Oh, Clark.

104
00:19:49,880 --> 00:19:52,440
Did you find what you were looking for?

105
00:19:53,240 --> 00:19:56,800
I thought, hoped...

106
00:19:57,600 --> 00:19:59,320
...it might still be there.

107
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:01,720
Your home?

108
00:20:04,120 --> 00:20:06,360
That place was a graveyard.

109
00:20:07,760 --> 00:20:09,160
I'm all that's left.

110
00:20:11,320 --> 00:20:14,720
Clark, the universe is a big place.

111
00:20:15,240 --> 00:20:17,400
And you don't know who's out there.

112
00:20:19,120 --> 00:20:21,480
And even if you are the last...

113
00:20:23,960 --> 00:20:25,720
...you're not alone.

114
00:20:30,360 --> 00:20:31,880
I know.

115
00:20:52,600 --> 00:20:53,720
- Sorry.
- Look out!

116
00:20:53,880 --> 00:20:55,080
Watch out, will you?

117
00:20:55,240 --> 00:20:56,680
- Excuse me.
- Sorry.

118
00:20:58,200 --> 00:20:59,480
Sorry.

119
00:21:00,920 --> 00:21:03,800
Great. Would you be careful?

120
00:21:04,760 --> 00:21:08,120
- Jimmy.
- Mr. Clark! I mean, Kent! Mr. Kent!

121
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:10,280
Welcome back! Oh, my God!

122
00:21:10,440 --> 00:21:14,040
Hey, come... Wait right there.
I'll be right back.

123
00:21:23,120 --> 00:21:26,440
Oh, hey, sorry, guys,
I'm still looking for a place to live...

124
00:21:26,600 --> 00:21:28,280
...if you know of anything reasonable.

125
00:21:28,440 --> 00:21:31,960
Behind you, Mr. Kent.
I made it myself. It's a cake.

126
00:21:33,760 --> 00:21:35,200
Oh, it looks...

127
00:21:36,200 --> 00:21:37,360
...delicious.

128
00:21:37,520 --> 00:21:41,680
Olsen! Where are the photos
of that birthday-clown-massacre thing?

129
00:21:41,840 --> 00:21:44,320
I'm on it, chief. Hey, look who's back.

130
00:21:44,720 --> 00:21:46,040
- Kent?
- Hey, chief.

131
00:21:46,200 --> 00:21:48,600
- Thank you for giving me my job back.
- Don't thank me.

132
00:21:48,760 --> 00:21:50,040
Thank Norm Palmer for dying.

133
00:21:51,840 --> 00:21:53,720
It was his time.

134
00:21:54,960 --> 00:21:58,400
- Let's get you set up, huh?
- Olsen!

135
00:21:58,560 --> 00:21:59,760
Okay, so I gotta run...

136
00:21:59,920 --> 00:22:03,080
...but I will be back to check on you
in a sec, Mr. Kent.

137
00:22:03,240 --> 00:22:07,240
Oh, hey, do you know
where I can find Lois?

138
00:22:20,600 --> 00:22:22,880
<i>The timing of this
automated-ignition countdown...</i>

139
00:22:23,040 --> 00:22:25,120
<i>...is the most precarious part
of the launch.</i>

140
00:22:25,520 --> 00:22:26,840
<i>Lois Lane, Daily Planet.</i>

141
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:30,120
<i>You also stated that the shuttle
will usher in a new era of travel...</i>

142
00:22:30,280 --> 00:22:33,200
<i>...enabling the average person
to afford transcontinental flights.</i>

143
00:22:33,360 --> 00:22:35,360
<i>But can you tell us the exact price...</i>

144
00:22:35,520 --> 00:22:38,000
<i>...an "average person"
will be expected to pay?</i>

145
00:22:38,200 --> 00:22:40,760
<i>The answer to that question
is in your press packet.</i>

146
00:22:40,920 --> 00:22:43,560
<i>The Earth is surrounded
by a blanket of air...</i>

147
00:22:43,720 --> 00:22:46,000
<i>...which we call the atmosphere.</i>

148
00:22:46,160 --> 00:22:49,600
<i>It reaches over...</i>

149
00:23:33,760 --> 00:23:36,440
Yeah. He looks just like his mom.

150
00:23:36,600 --> 00:23:40,440
Already takes after her too, especially
when it comes to getting into trouble.

151
00:23:40,600 --> 00:23:42,040
Mother?

152
00:23:43,800 --> 00:23:48,280
Oh, yeah, well, I guess you've been gone.
Fearless reporter Lois Lane is a mommy.

153
00:23:50,520 --> 00:23:53,680
Oh, you know, I'll just...
I'll take that. That's good.

154
00:23:53,840 --> 00:23:56,640
- Sorry.
- No. She's got plenty.

155
00:23:56,800 --> 00:23:58,680
- Wait, she's married?
- Yes.

156
00:23:59,160 --> 00:24:03,040
No. Not really. It's more like
a prolonged engagement.

157
00:24:03,200 --> 00:24:05,560
But don't ask Miss Lane
when they're tying the knot...

158
00:24:05,720 --> 00:24:09,120
...because she hates that question.

159
00:24:09,280 --> 00:24:13,560
<i>- like this follow the same stringent
safety guidelines set by NASA?</i>

160
00:24:13,720 --> 00:24:16,240
<i>Since this is a joint venture
with the Air Force...</i>

161
00:24:16,400 --> 00:24:19,760
You all right? You look like
you could use a drink.

162
00:24:22,080 --> 00:24:25,200
This place is so tacky.
Why are we back here?

163
00:24:25,360 --> 00:24:28,840
Kitty, while you were doing your nails
and ordering fur coats online...

164
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:30,680
...I was busy unlocking the secrets...

165
00:24:30,840 --> 00:24:33,600
...of one of the most advanced
civilizations in the universe.

166
00:24:33,760 --> 00:24:34,960
Weren't there two of those?

167
00:24:35,120 --> 00:24:39,200
You see, unlike our clunky
earthbound forms of construction...

168
00:24:39,360 --> 00:24:41,720
...the technology on Krypton,
Superman's home world...

169
00:24:41,880 --> 00:24:44,200
...was based on manipulating
the growth of crystals.

170
00:24:44,360 --> 00:24:45,680
Sounds like hocus-pocus to me.

171
00:24:45,840 --> 00:24:49,440
Well, naturally, to the primitive mind,
any sufficiently advanced technology...

172
00:24:49,600 --> 00:24:51,640
...would be indistinguishable from magic.

173
00:24:51,800 --> 00:24:56,000
But imagine: cities, vehicles, weapons...

174
00:24:56,560 --> 00:24:58,120
...entire continents...

175
00:24:58,440 --> 00:25:01,080
...all grown.

176
00:25:08,440 --> 00:25:11,640
To think that one could create
a new world...

177
00:25:11,800 --> 00:25:14,680
...with such a simple little object.

178
00:25:16,320 --> 00:25:18,520
It's like a seed.

179
00:25:18,680 --> 00:25:20,840
And all it needs is water.

180
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:22,400
Like...

181
00:25:23,160 --> 00:25:25,080
...Sea-Monkeys.

182
00:25:26,680 --> 00:25:28,880
Exactly, Kitty.

183
00:25:29,400 --> 00:25:31,000
Like Sea-Monkeys.

184
00:25:33,120 --> 00:25:37,520
Clark has been doing a little
soul-searching for the last couple years.

185
00:25:37,680 --> 00:25:39,600
- He saw Ilamas.
- Yeah?

186
00:25:39,760 --> 00:25:41,720
- Yeah.
- Must be tough coming back.

187
00:25:43,360 --> 00:25:45,440
- Coming back?
- To work.

188
00:25:46,320 --> 00:25:47,720
Yeah.

189
00:25:48,120 --> 00:25:50,600
Well, you know, things change.

190
00:25:50,760 --> 00:25:52,720
I mean, of course things change...

191
00:25:52,880 --> 00:25:58,520
...but sometimes things that you didn't
think would change could change.

192
00:25:58,960 --> 00:26:00,480
Take Lois.

193
00:26:00,640 --> 00:26:04,440
A woman like her,
I never thought she'd settle down.

194
00:26:04,880 --> 00:26:08,400
You know, if you ask me...
Because she'll never tell you this...

195
00:26:08,560 --> 00:26:13,240
...but if you ask me,
she's still in love with you-know-who.

196
00:26:21,240 --> 00:26:24,960
The original space shuttle
generated 7.5 million pounds of thrust...

197
00:26:25,120 --> 00:26:26,760
...just in the initial launch phase.

198
00:26:26,920 --> 00:26:31,480
But, by piggybacking
on this Boeing 777... Yes?

199
00:26:31,640 --> 00:26:33,600
If this launch is as pivotal as you claim...

200
00:26:33,760 --> 00:26:35,960
...why is it being covered
by one news network?

201
00:26:36,120 --> 00:26:39,200
Why don't we save those questions
for the post-launch briefing.

202
00:26:39,360 --> 00:26:40,920
How about that, Miss Lane?

203
00:26:41,080 --> 00:26:44,400
When we hit 40,000 feet,
the shuttle will detach, ascend...

204
00:26:44,560 --> 00:26:48,120
...and then fire the first of two propellant
systems, the liquid fuel boosters.

205
00:26:48,280 --> 00:26:50,240
When the shuttle
reaches the stratosphere...

206
00:26:50,400 --> 00:26:52,440
...the secondary
insertion booster will fire...

207
00:26:52,600 --> 00:26:55,840
...propelling the craft
at 4gs into the mesosphere.

208
00:26:59,520 --> 00:27:01,600
- Careful.
- I know.

209
00:27:02,400 --> 00:27:05,280
- Careful. Careful.
- I know.

210
00:27:31,400 --> 00:27:33,760
Wow, that's really something, Lex.

211
00:27:33,920 --> 00:27:36,120
Wait for it.

212
00:27:39,400 --> 00:27:42,040
Wow, that's really something, Lex.

213
00:27:44,400 --> 00:27:47,000
<i>It's freaking Gone With the Wind.</i>

214
00:27:47,640 --> 00:27:49,600
- Shut off the camera.
- But I'm getting it.

215
00:27:49,760 --> 00:27:51,720
I said, shut off the damn camera.

216
00:27:57,840 --> 00:27:59,480
I think I did something wrong.

217
00:27:59,640 --> 00:28:03,800
No. That wasn't you.

218
00:28:30,240 --> 00:28:33,760
<i>Ignition is at T minus one minute
and we are prepping for separation.</i>

219
00:28:33,920 --> 00:28:35,360
CDR., start the clock.

220
00:28:35,960 --> 00:28:38,200
<i>Three minutes and counting.</i>

221
00:28:38,360 --> 00:28:40,520
<i>Body signs normal. Crew is looking good.</i>

222
00:28:40,680 --> 00:28:42,280
Shuttle readouts are holding steady.

223
00:28:42,440 --> 00:28:44,600
<i>- We're still a go for launch.
- Roger.</i>

224
00:28:51,800 --> 00:28:54,560
<i>- Houston, you copy?
- Houston, do you copy?</i>

225
00:28:58,360 --> 00:28:59,360
Oh, God.

226
00:29:00,760 --> 00:29:02,440
<i>Electrical variance.</i>

227
00:29:06,080 --> 00:29:07,560
What the...?

228
00:29:14,160 --> 00:29:16,120
Please, there's nothing to worry about.

229
00:29:16,280 --> 00:29:20,360
It seems that we are experiencing
a slight power outage.

230
00:29:24,160 --> 00:29:27,480
- What did you do?
- It wasn't me. It just cycled back up.

231
00:29:28,960 --> 00:29:30,560
<i>Genesis, radio check from Houston.</i>

232
00:29:32,120 --> 00:29:34,520
There we have it.
We were experiencing a power outage.

233
00:29:36,840 --> 00:29:39,320
<i>- Climbing to 40,000 feet.
- Roger, 40,000 feet.</i>

234
00:29:50,360 --> 00:29:52,920
<i>And it's gone! A blazing fastball...</i>

235
00:30:13,520 --> 00:30:14,680
Is that it?

236
00:30:20,640 --> 00:30:22,880
I don't think so.

237
00:31:10,320 --> 00:31:12,680
<i>Dual engine failure,
but they're up and running again.</i>

238
00:31:12,840 --> 00:31:16,560
<i>Genesis, I hate to say this, but it looks
like we're gonna have to scrub the launch.</i>

239
00:31:16,720 --> 00:31:20,120
- Aborting booster ignition.
- Roger. Aborting booster ignition.

240
00:31:21,760 --> 00:31:24,880
Boosters are non-responsive.
We're still counting down for ignition.

241
00:31:25,040 --> 00:31:26,680
<i>- Platform, we have a problem.
- Go.</i>

242
00:31:26,840 --> 00:31:29,160
<i>Looks like something faulted
during the power outage.</i>

243
00:31:29,320 --> 00:31:31,560
<i>Both boosters are
