00:59:18,200 --> 00:59:20,840
<i>Satellites have proven
most ineffective at tracking him.</i>

481
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:24,400
<i>He might literally be moving
near the speed of light.</i>

482
00:59:37,080 --> 00:59:39,840
<i>- Our map is illuminated with sightings...
- Kent!</i>

483
00:59:40,000 --> 00:59:42,920
<i>- The chief is waiting.
...on every continent, giving citizens...</i>

484
00:59:46,640 --> 00:59:50,200
These are iconic, and they were taken
by a 12-year-old with a camera phone.

485
00:59:50,360 --> 00:59:53,400
- What do you got, Olsen?
- I got those.

486
00:59:55,560 --> 00:59:57,240
- Look, in the sky, chief.
- It's a bird.

487
00:59:57,400 --> 00:59:58,920
- It's a plane.
- No, look, it's...

488
00:59:59,640 --> 01:00:00,800
You wanted to see me?

489
01:00:01,680 --> 01:00:03,320
Yeah, Kent, come on in. Sit down.

490
01:00:03,480 --> 01:00:06,360
I wanna talk a little strategy. Okay.

491
01:00:06,840 --> 01:00:09,400
First off, Lois, I don't understand
what you're doing...

492
01:00:09,560 --> 01:00:12,720
...sneaking around covering the blackout.
- It wasn't just a blackout.

493
01:00:12,880 --> 01:00:14,800
Cellphones, pagers,
automobiles, airplane...

494
01:00:14,960 --> 01:00:17,320
Every other paper in town
has got a female reporter...

495
01:00:17,480 --> 01:00:20,760
...a good-looking female reporter,
stashed on the roof covering Superman.

496
01:00:20,920 --> 01:00:24,440
- And you two are the ones with history.
- Chief, I've done Superman.

497
01:00:26,040 --> 01:00:28,000
Covered him. You know what I mean.

498
01:00:28,160 --> 01:00:30,240
Yeah, that makes you an expert.
Do him again.

499
01:00:30,400 --> 01:00:33,080
- There are a dozen other stories out there.
- Yeah? Name one.

500
01:00:33,240 --> 01:00:35,720
Well, there was a museum robbery
last night.

501
01:00:36,200 --> 01:00:39,520
Even Superman missed that one.
He was too busy saving this hooker.

502
01:00:39,680 --> 01:00:42,240
Why don't you guys
track down Lex Luthor?

503
01:00:42,920 --> 01:00:45,080
Well, no one's seen him
since his fifth appeal.

504
01:00:45,240 --> 01:00:47,320
He's got more history
with Superman than anyone.

505
01:00:47,480 --> 01:00:48,920
Maybe he's got something to say.

506
01:00:49,080 --> 01:00:52,680
- Luthor's yesterday's news.
- No, I like that idea.

507
01:00:53,600 --> 01:00:57,960
Perry, Lex Luthor is a career criminal
who nearly killed him, for God's sakes.

508
01:00:58,120 --> 01:01:00,280
Jimmy, how did Lex Luthor
get out of prison?

509
01:01:00,440 --> 01:01:04,280
Well, the appeals court called Superman
as a witness and he wasn't around.

510
01:01:04,960 --> 01:01:07,000
How much do you think
that pisses off Superman?

511
01:01:07,160 --> 01:01:08,720
- Give him to someone else.
- A lot.

512
01:01:08,880 --> 01:01:10,720
- A lot.
- Polly. Give him to Polly.

513
01:01:15,640 --> 01:01:17,120
Lois, Superman.

514
01:01:17,280 --> 01:01:19,400
- What about the blackout?
- Kent, blackout.

515
01:01:21,880 --> 01:01:24,120
Great. Thanks, chief.

516
01:01:27,120 --> 01:01:31,760
Lois, I'm sorry. I'd hate if this
damaged our relationship.

517
01:01:33,040 --> 01:01:34,120
Relationship?

518
01:01:34,840 --> 01:01:36,200
- Yeah.
- Hi, Mommy.

519
01:01:36,360 --> 01:01:38,160
- Hi, you.
- Hey, guys.

520
01:01:38,320 --> 01:01:41,960
He got an A in science, but a D in gym,
so we're doing something right.

521
01:01:42,120 --> 01:01:44,040
- Yeah, at least one of us is.
- What?

522
01:01:44,200 --> 01:01:46,920
It's Perry. He just shoved Superman
back into my life.

523
01:01:47,080 --> 01:01:49,920
Well, honey, I'm sure you can
find a way to interview Superman...

524
01:01:50,080 --> 01:01:52,000
...without bringing him
back into your life.

525
01:01:52,160 --> 01:01:56,280
<i>There's really no way around it, folks.
Superman is back in all of our lives.</i>

526
01:01:57,680 --> 01:01:59,400
<i>We're coming to you from Sydney...</i>

527
01:01:59,560 --> 01:02:03,200
<i>...where people have gathered
on these rooftops to scour the sky...</i>

528
01:02:03,360 --> 01:02:06,440
Okay, how about this?
We'll stay late. We'll get dinner.

529
01:02:06,600 --> 01:02:10,080
I'll help with Superman, and you and
Clark can work on the blackout together.

530
01:02:10,240 --> 01:02:13,080
- Is that all right with you, Clark?
- Swell.

531
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:39,880
I was gonna pretend
the brakes were out.

532
01:02:40,040 --> 01:02:43,040
Pretend. Like we talked about.

533
01:02:43,200 --> 01:02:45,880
You didn't actually have to cut them!

534
01:02:46,040 --> 01:02:47,280
Of course I did.

535
01:02:47,440 --> 01:02:52,080
A man can always tell when a woman
is pretending, especially Superman.

536
01:02:56,760 --> 01:02:59,040
So did you get your rock?

537
01:03:00,360 --> 01:03:02,200
I did.

538
01:03:03,520 --> 01:03:07,400
<i>U.S. Coast Guard issuing a small-craft
advisory for the Metropolis ocean area.</i>

539
01:03:07,560 --> 01:03:09,320
<i>High-wind advisory is in effect...</i>

540
01:03:09,480 --> 01:03:12,240
<i>...ocean currents and tides
becoming increasingly dangerous.</i>

541
01:03:12,400 --> 01:03:15,480
<i>All warnings lasting
until later this evening.</i>

542
01:03:15,640 --> 01:03:16,840
<i>Security, security.</i>

543
01:03:17,000 --> 01:03:22,240
<i>This is U.S. Coast Guard issuing
a small-craft advisory for northeast seas.</i>

544
01:03:22,400 --> 01:03:26,680
<i>Winds reaching 50 miles per hour,
high tides in the morning.</i>

545
01:03:26,840 --> 01:03:28,600
<i>Waves reaching 20 to 30 feet.</i>

546
01:03:28,760 --> 01:03:32,600
<i>This warning is in effect for
all small crafts for the next four hours.</i>

547
01:03:55,720 --> 01:03:57,280
Weird. If these times are right...

548
01:03:57,440 --> 01:04:00,400
...the blackout spread
from a specific origin point.

549
01:04:00,560 --> 01:04:01,880
Where?

550
01:04:02,040 --> 01:04:03,760
I'm not sure yet.

551
01:04:04,440 --> 01:04:07,960
With the super-hearing, does he hear each
sound by itself or everything at once?

552
01:04:08,320 --> 01:04:09,520
<i>Both.</i>

553
01:04:09,680 --> 01:04:11,800
<i>- He's certainly taller than I thought.
- 6'4".</i>

554
01:04:11,960 --> 01:04:15,560
I love that he can see through anything.
I'd have fun with that.

555
01:04:15,920 --> 01:04:17,560
<i>Anything but lead.</i>

556
01:04:20,680 --> 01:04:21,880
- I bet he's...
- 225 pounds...

557
01:04:22,040 --> 01:04:23,640
...faster than a speeding bullet...

558
01:04:23,800 --> 01:04:27,120
...draws his power from the sun,
invulnerable to anything but kryptonite...

559
01:04:27,280 --> 01:04:29,240
...and he never lies.
- Kryptonite?

560
01:04:29,400 --> 01:04:31,640
Radioactive pieces of his home world.

561
01:04:31,800 --> 01:04:33,920
It's deadly. To him.

562
01:04:38,320 --> 01:04:41,560
Lois, how tall would you say Clark is?

563
01:04:43,040 --> 01:04:44,960
<i>About 6'3", 6'4".</i>

564
01:04:45,120 --> 01:04:47,800
<i>About 200, 215 pounds?</i>

565
01:04:57,360 --> 01:05:01,200
Jimmy, Jason, let's go get these intrepid
reporters something to keep them going.

566
01:05:01,360 --> 01:05:03,160
- Burritos!
- Come here, canhead.

567
01:05:04,600 --> 01:05:08,400
We're going this way. Do they have
anything other than burritos?

568
01:05:09,240 --> 01:05:11,480
I think they have fries and burgers.

569
01:05:11,640 --> 01:05:14,040
So have you found a place to live yet?

570
01:05:14,200 --> 01:05:15,720
No. I'm still looking.

571
01:05:16,440 --> 01:05:18,840
You know, Lois, I wanted to ask you
about that artic...

572
01:05:19,000 --> 01:05:22,360
Hey, I'm gonna run downstairs
for some fresh air. Great!

573
01:05:35,560 --> 01:05:37,200
Thanks.

574
01:05:44,680 --> 01:05:47,320
- Let's talk when I get back.
- Sure.

575
01:06:38,640 --> 01:06:41,280
You know, you really
shouldn't smoke, Miss Lane.

576
01:06:44,440 --> 01:06:46,840
- Sorry. Didn't mean to startle you.
- I'm fine. Really.

577
01:06:48,880 --> 01:06:51,880
I just wasn't expecting you.

578
01:06:52,520 --> 01:06:54,040
With all the press on the plane...

579
01:06:54,200 --> 01:06:56,520
...I wasn't sure it was
the best time for us to talk.

580
01:06:56,680 --> 01:06:59,720
Well, there's no press around now.
Except for me, of course.

581
01:07:01,840 --> 01:07:04,200
I know people are asking questions
now that I'm back.

582
01:07:04,560 --> 01:07:07,960
I think it's only fair
that I answer those people.

583
01:07:09,560 --> 01:07:12,760
So you're here for an interview?

584
01:07:13,960 --> 01:07:14,960
Okay, then.

585
01:07:18,680 --> 01:07:20,600
- Where did I put that thing?
- Right pocket.

586
01:07:26,480 --> 01:07:29,080
Let's start with the big question.

587
01:07:29,240 --> 01:07:31,640
- Where'd you go?
- To Krypton.

588
01:07:31,800 --> 01:07:34,080
But you told me it was destroyed.
Ages ago.

589
01:07:34,240 --> 01:07:35,640
It was.

590
01:07:35,800 --> 01:07:38,080
But when astronomers
thought they found it...

591
01:07:39,480 --> 01:07:41,760
...I had to see for myself.

592
01:07:45,240 --> 01:07:48,920
Well, you're back, and everyone
seems to be pretty happy about it.

593
01:07:52,000 --> 01:07:53,400
Not everyone.

594
01:07:54,520 --> 01:07:56,840
- I read the article, Lois.
- So did a lot of people.

595
01:07:57,000 --> 01:07:59,840
- Tomorrow they're giving me the Pulitzer...
- Why did you write it?

596
01:08:01,440 --> 01:08:03,400
How could you leave us like that?

597
01:08:04,840 --> 01:08:07,160
I moved on. So did the rest of us.

598
01:08:07,640 --> 01:08:09,080
That's why I wrote it.

599
01:08:09,240 --> 01:08:11,920
The world doesn't need a savior.

600
01:08:12,320 --> 01:08:14,160
And neither do I.

601
01:08:28,680 --> 01:08:29,720
Lois.

602
01:08:31,360 --> 01:08:33,720
Will you come with me?

603
01:08:35,400 --> 01:08:36,920
Why?

604
01:08:37,280 --> 01:08:39,320
There's something I wanna show you.

605
01:08:45,320 --> 01:08:47,040
Please.

606
01:08:57,600 --> 01:08:59,680
I can't be gone long.

607
01:08:59,840 --> 01:09:01,680
You won't be.

608
01:09:13,560 --> 01:09:16,200
Clark said the reason you left
without saying goodbye...

609
01:09:16,360 --> 01:09:18,560
...is because it was
too unbearable for you.

610
01:09:18,720 --> 01:09:21,240
Personally, I think that's a load of crap.

611
01:09:21,800 --> 01:09:24,840
- Clark?
- He's just a guy I work with.

612
01:09:25,880 --> 01:09:27,920
Maybe Clark's right.

613
01:09:31,160 --> 01:09:33,200
You know, my...

614
01:09:33,360 --> 01:09:38,200
Richard, he's a pilot.
He takes me up all the time.

615
01:09:39,320 --> 01:09:41,240
Not like this.

616
01:09:55,480 --> 01:09:57,800
I forgot how warm you were.

617
01:10:27,160 --> 01:10:28,600
Listen.

618
01:10:29,440 --> 01:10:31,280
What do you hear?

619
01:10:31,960 --> 01:10:33,160
Nothing.

620
01:10:36,920 --> 01:10:38,600
I hear everything.

621
01:10:41,920 --> 01:10:44,440
You wrote that the world
doesn't need a savior...

622
01:10:45,720 --> 01:10:48,920
...but every day
I hear people crying for one.

623
01:11:01,240 --> 01:11:03,800
I'm sorry I left you, Lois.

624
01:11:07,520 --> 01:11:09,480
I'll take you back now.

625
01:13:17,160 --> 01:13:18,720
Richard's a good man.

626
01:13:22,000 --> 01:13:24,120
And you've been gone a long time.

627
01:13:26,680 --> 01:13:28,200
I know.

628
01:13:32,760 --> 01:13:34,040
I...

629
01:13:39,040 --> 01:13:40,960
So will I see you around?

630
01:13:41,920 --> 01:13:43,840
I'm always around.

631
01:13:45,080 --> 01:13:46,720
Good night, Lois.

632
01:14:04,920 --> 01:14:08,640
We're having beef, honey. Do you want
the tofu wrap or the veggie wrap?

633
01:14:12,280 --> 01:14:13,800
You all right?

634
01:14:15,560 --> 01:14:16,920
Where have you been?

635
01:14:21,080 --> 01:14:26,520
I was up on the roof, getting some air.

636
01:14:27,160 --> 01:14:29,040
Tell the truth now.

637
01:14:35,320 --> 01:14:36,440
Were you smoking?

638
01:14:38,960 --> 01:14:40,640
No.

639
01:14:49,080 --> 01:14:50,240
Is this real?

640
01:14:51,240 --> 01:14:53,040
- Where'd you find him?
- He found me.

641
01:14:53,200 --> 01:14:55,880
Oh, this is great. I can't wait to read it.

642
01:14:56,040 --> 01:14:58,360
So, Mr. White, about the blackout...

643
01:14:58,520 --> 01:15:00,920
Lois, this is the biggest night
of your life.

644
01:15:01,080 --> 01:15:03,160
Have you picked out a dress?
Something snazzy?

645
01:15:04,120 --> 01:15:06,720
It just feels a little weird
winning for that article.

646
01:15:06,880 --> 01:15:09,800
- It just doesn't seem right.
- What doesn't seem right?

647
01:15:09,960 --> 01:15:13,400
Winning an award for an article called
"Why the World Doesn't Need Superman."

648
01:15:13,560 --> 01:15:15,920
When, according
to this newspaper, they do.

649
01:15:16,080 --> 01:15:18,880
Lois, Pulitzer Prizes
are like Academy Awards.

650
01:15:19,040 --> 01:15:22,040
Nobody remembers what you got one for.
It's just that you got one.

651
01:15:22,200 --> 01:15:25,200
- But...
- This is your night. You enjoy it.

652
01:15:25,360 --> 01:15:27,800
I'm sure Kent's on the blackout.

653
01:16:25,960 --> 01:16:28,080
Department of Water and Power, please.

654
01:16:28,760 --> 01:16:30,000
7782, great.

655
01:16:31,400 --> 01:16:32,840
Metropolis Public Works.

656
01:16:33,000 --> 01:16:35,400
<i>Hi, Stephen, Lois Lane
from the Daily Planet. Blackout?</i>

657
01:16:35,560 --> 01:16:38,160
I just need a little info
on a few outstanding power grids.

658
01:16:38,320 --> 01:16:39,880
<i>Yeah, I do have it here, actually.</i>

659
01:16:40,040 --> 01:16:43,880
<i>So the uptown grid went dark at 12:36
and midtown 10 seconds before.</i>

660
01:16:44,040 --> 01:16:45,480
Which grid was hit first?

661
01:16:45,640 --> 01:16:46,920
<i>It just reads Vanderworth.</i>

662
01:16:47,080 --> 01:16:49,360
<i>- Across the river?
- 6 Springwood Drive.</i>

663
01:16:49,520 --> 01:16:51,680
6 Springwood Drive.
A residence or a business?

664
01:16:51,840 --> 01:16:53,520
<i>- Residence.
- Sure? Nothing before that?</i>

665
01:16:53,680 --> 01:16:55,920
<i>- That's all it shows.
- Thank you very much.</i>

666
01:16:57,680 --> 01:16:58,920
Oh, Jason.

667
01:17:05,440 --> 01:17:08,520
- There's your mom, Jason.
- You're late, Mommy.

668
01:17:16,400 --> 01:17:19,120
Where are we? Is this the Pulitzer?

669
01:17:19,280 --> 01:17:23,400
Nope. I've just gotta ask these people
a few questions and then we can go.

670
01:17:37,120 --> 01:17:39,400
Can I stay in the car?

671
01:17:39,920 --> 01:17:41,440
No, honey.

672
01:17:47,840 --> 01:17:52,040
- Are we trespassing?
- No. Yes.

673
01:18:06,160 --> 01:18:07,920
Hello?

674
01:18:38,120 --> 01:18:39,600
Hello?

675
01:18:50,240 --> 01:18:52,720
I like the curly one.

676
01:18:59,720 --> 01:19:02,440
Let's go. This was a bad idea.

677
01:19:17,520 --> 01:19:19,240
Lex Luthor.

678
01:19:21,160 --> 01:19:23,200
Lois Lane?

679
01:19:28,760 --> 01:19:30,040
You're bald.

680
01:19:49,320 --> 01:19:50,640
And what is your name?

681
01:19:50,800 --> 01:19:53,160
I'm not supposed to talk to strangers.

682
01:19:53,640 --> 01:19:55,520
- Cute kid, and smart.
- Thanks.

683
01:19:55,680 --> 01:19:58,760
We're not really strangers, are we?
This is kind of a little reunion.

684
01:19:58,920 --> 01:20:00,880
Heck, I'm a fan.

685
01:20:01,040 --> 01:20:02,480
I love your writing...

686
01:20:03,280 --> 01:20:05,040
...and your dress.
- I love your boat.

687
01:20:05,200 --> 01:20:07,720
How'd you get it?
Swindle some widow out of her money?

688
01:20:09,000 --> 01:20:11,160
That's funny. Didn't you win
the Pulitzer Prize...

689
01:20:11,320 --> 01:20:14,760
...for my favorite article of all time, "Why
the World Doesn't Need Superman"?

690
01:20:14,920 --> 01:20:18,680
Didn't you have a few more years to go
on that double life sentence?

691
01:20:18,840 --> 01:20:21,000
Yes, well, we can thank
the Man of Steel for that.

692
01:20:21,160 --> 01:20:24,320
I mean, he's really good at swooping in
and catching the bad guys...

693
01:20:24,480 --> 01:20:27,880
...but he's not so hot at the little things,
like Miranda rights...

694
01:20:28,040 --> 01:20:32,560
...due process, making your court date.

695
01:20:32,720 --> 01:20:35,080
Did you have anything to do
with the blackout?

696
01:20:37,960 --> 01:20:40,080
Are you fishing for an interview,
Miss Lane?

697
01:20:40,240 --> 01:20:42,320
It's been a while
since you've been a headline.

698
01:20:42,480 --> 01:20:44,560
Maybe it's time
people knew your name again.

699
01:20:45,200 --> 01:20:49,000
How about we turn this boat around,
call a cab for my son...

700
01:20:49,520 --> 01:20:52,040
...and then you can do
whatever you want with me.

701
01:20:52,720 --> 01:20:55,160
No, I don't think we'll be
turning around, Miss Lane...

702
01:20:55,320 --> 01:20:57,840
...which means that
we do have some time to kill.

703
01:20:59,920 --> 01:21:01,720
How about that interview?

704
01:21:02,600 --> 01:21:05,800
Yeah, just call me if you hear anything.
Okay. Thank you.

705
01:21:05,960 --> 01:21:07,600
So, what did the school say?

706
01:21:07,760 --> 01:21:09,200
She picked him up at 3:15.

707
01:21:13,280 --> 01:21:16,440
- Hi, I heard about Lois.
- Yes, come in, Clark, come in.

708
01:21:16,600 --> 01:21:19,000
- Is there anything I can do?
- Yeah, you're a reporter.

709
01:21:19,160 --> 01:21:21,800
- Help Richard track her down.
- I'll check her computer.

710
01:21:21,960 --> 01:21:23,160
Excuse me, Clark.

711
01:21:36,320 --> 01:21:39,280
What do you know about crystals?

712
01:21:39,440 --> 01:21:41,080
They make great chandeliers.

713
01:21:41,640 --> 01:21:46,440
This crystal may seem unremarkable,
but so is the seed of a redwood tree.

714
01:21:46,600 --> 01:21:49,880
It's how our mutual friend in tights
made his Arctic getaway spot.

715
01:21:50,040 --> 01:21:51,840
Cute. It's a little small for my taste.

716
01:21:52,000 --> 01:21:53,480
You're building an island?

717
01:21:54,640 --> 01:21:57,840
You're not seeing
the big picture here, Miss Lane.

718
01:21:58,000 --> 01:22:00,200
Let me enlarge it for you.

719
01:22:02,680 --> 01:22:05,960
Not just an island,
an entirely new continent.

720
01:22:06,120 --> 01:22:09,240
An extinct world, reborn on our own.

721
01:22:09,400 --> 01:22:10,760
Why?

722
01:22:13,640 --> 01:22:15,480
Land, Miss Lane.

723
01:22:15,640 --> 01:22:18,280
I mean... Kitty, what did my father
used to say to me?

724
01:22:18,440 --> 01:22:19,800
"You're losing your hair"?

725
01:22:20,760 --> 01:22:22,600
- Before that.
- "Get out"?

726
01:22:24,080 --> 01:22:26,280
He said, "You can print money...

727
01:22:26,440 --> 01:22:28,960
...manufacture diamonds,
and people are a dime a dozen...

728
01:22:29,120 --> 01:22:32,080
...but they'll always need land."

729
01:22:32,240 --> 01:22:34,960
It's the one thing
they're not making any more of.

730
01:22:35,480 --> 01:22:37,760
But the United States...

731
01:22:39,400 --> 01:22:42,760
Will be underwater.

732
01:22:43,160 --> 01:22:44,680
It's simple physics, Miss Lane.

733
01:22:44,840 --> 01:22:47,520
Two objects cannot occupy
the same space at the same time.

734
01:22:47,680 --> 01:22:50,120
And the rest of the world
will just let you keep it?

735
01:22:50,280 --> 01:22:52,400
- They'll...
- They'll...

736
01:22:52,880 --> 01:22:54,280
...what?

737
01:22:54,440 --> 01:22:57,200
I'll have advanced alien technology...

738
01:22:57,360 --> 01:23:00,280
...thousands of years beyond
what anyone could throw at me.

739
01:23:00,440 --> 01:23:02,400
Bring it on!

740
01:23:03,360 --> 01:23:05,200
And eventually...

741
01:23:05,360 --> 01:23:07,600
...the rest of the world
will be begging me...

742
01:23:07,760 --> 01:23:10,280
...for a piece of high-tech
beachfront property.

743
01:23:10,440 --> 01:23:12,680
In fact, they'll pay
through the nose for it.

744
01:23:13,080 --> 01:23:14,760
But millions of people will die.

745
01:23:14,920 --> 01:23:17,440
Billions! Once again,
the press underestimates me.

746
01:23:17,600 --> 01:23:19,880
This is front-page news.

747
01:23:20,520 --> 01:23:22,440
Come on, let me hear you say it
just once.

748
01:23:22,600 --> 01:23:26,920
- You're insane.
- No! Not that. No, the other thing.

749
01:23:27,080 --> 01:23:30,600
It's dangling off the tip of your tongue.
Let me hear it just once, please?

750
01:23:30,760 --> 01:23:33,640
- Superman will never...
- Wrong!

751
01:23:46,320 --> 01:23:47,880
What is that?

752
01:23:49,040 --> 01:23:51,720
I think you know exactly what this is.

753
01:23:57,480 --> 01:24:00,240
Mind over muscle, Miss Lane.

754
01:24:01,320 --> 01:24:03,040
Mind...

755
01:24:10,280 --> 01:24:12,200
Who is that boy's father?

756
01:24:13,640 --> 01:24:15,440
Richard.

757
01:24:15,880 --> 01:24:19,240
<i>Mr. Luthor, we're approaching
the coordinates.</i>

758
01:24:19,800 --> 01:24:21,320
Are you sure?

759
01:24:21,480 --> 01:24:26,600
<i>Yes, sir. Latitude 40 degrees north,
longitude 73 degrees west.</i>

760
01:24:47,240 --> 01:24:49,320
Don't let them leave this room.

761
01:24:49,640 --> 01:24:52,120
Kitty, come with me.
You're not gonna want to miss this.

762
01:26:02,200 --> 01:26:03,520
- Damn it.
- What?

763
01:26:03,680 --> 01:26:04,840
She has a password.

764
01:26:06,760 --> 01:26:08,280
"Jason."

765
01:26:10,280 --> 01:26:11,920
"Richard."

766
01:26:13,760 --> 01:26:15,280
Try "Superman."

767
01:26:20,200 --> 01:26:22,520
"Superman." Great.

768
01:26:30,520 --> 01:26:32,520
Don't touch that, honey.

769
01:26:36,600 --> 01:26:38,960
Why don't you go play the piano.

770
01:28:31,400 --> 01:28:33,800
Come on, come on, come on.

771
01:30:16,480 --> 01:30:19,400
Lex, this isn't like the train set.

772
01:30:21,240 --> 01:30:22,920
I know.

773
01:30:28,720 --> 01:30:30,440
Come on, come on.

774
01:30:31,040 --> 01:30:32,200
Come on.

775
01:31:56,520 --> 01:31:58,320
- Honey, are you okay?
- Yeah.

776
01:31:58,480 --> 01:32:00,400
- Are you hurt?
- I'm fine.

777
01:32:01,560 --> 01:32:04,200
Open this door! Open it!

778
01:32:18,920 --> 01:32:21,200
Could you help Mommy open the door?

779
01:32:23,960 --> 01:32:25,640
I'm sorry.

780
01:32:28,600 --> 01:32:30,600
It's gonna be okay.

781
01:32:30,760 --> 01:32:33,000
Okay? It's gonna be okay.

782
01:32:51,880 --> 01:32:55,200
We had a little problem downstairs.

783
01:32:55,720 --> 01:32:57,800
Brutus is dead.

784
01:32:58,440 --> 01:33:01,560
He got hit with the piano.

785
01:33:05,960 --> 01:33:07,760
Where's the boy?

786
01:33:07,920 --> 01:33:11,880
With the mother,
locked up in the pantry.

787
01:33:13,960 --> 01:33:16,040
Oh, it's time for us to go.

788
01:33:21,800 --> 01:33:24,200
My camera's not working.

789
01:33:24,960 --> 01:33:27,000
And my phone's not working.

790
01:33:31,840 --> 01:33:34,480
- Okay, I'm good.
- That was weird.

791
01:33:48,840 --> 01:33:51,080
Hey, guys.
This just came through the fax.

792
01:33:51,240 --> 01:33:53,440
It's Lois' handwriting,
I'd recognize it anywhere.

793
01:33:53,600 --> 01:33:55,360
I just... No idea
what the numbers mean.

794
01:33:55,520 --> 01:33:57,200
- They're coordinates.
- Coordinates.

795
01:33:59,240 --> 01:34:00,400
That's just off the coast.

796
01:34:00,560 --> 01:34:03,560
Jimmy, tell Perry I'm taking the seaplane.
Keep trying her cell.

797
01:36:02,640 --> 01:36:04,040
What are these, lottery numbers?

798
01:36:04,560 --> 01:36:06,480
I think they're coordinates, chief.

799
01:36:43,600 --> 01:36:44,720
Chief...

800
01:37:10,520 --> 01:37:12,720
Come on! Move it!

801
01:39:30,520 --> 01:39:32,200
Chief!

802
01:39:42,880 --> 01:39:45,200
Great Caesar's ghost.

803
01:41:46,960 --> 01:41:49,000
- Daddy.
- Oh, my God.

804
01:42:02,040 --> 01:42:03,400
How did you get here?

805
01:42:03,560 --> 01:42:05,160
I flew.

806
01:42:08,680 --> 01:42:10,440
Look out!

807
01:42:22,760 --> 01:42:24,400
Mom!

808
01:42:24,560 --> 01:42:26,600
Mom! Mom!

809
01:42:26,760 --> 01:42:28,080
Jason, come here! Jason!

810
01:42:30,840 --> 01:42:32,680
Come here! Watch your head!
Come here!

811
01:43:30,720 --> 01:43:32,440
Mommy! Mom!

812
01:43:34,280 --> 01:43:35,480
Jason!

813
01:43:38,800 --> 01:43:40,240
Jason, hold on!

814
01:43:43,240 --> 01:43:45,800
- Have you got him?
- I got him! Go!

815
01:43:48,120 --> 01:43:49,640
Hold on! Hold on!

816
01:44:03,760 --> 01:44:05,040
- Mommy!
- Give him to me!

817
01:44:05,200 --> 01:44:06,720
Mommy!

818
01:44:07,320 --> 01:44:09,160
- Mommy! Mommy!
- Come on, Jason! Come on!

819
01:44:12,840 --> 01:44:15,560
- Lois! Lois!
- Mommy!

820
01:45:17,400 --> 01:45:19,400
Jason, get on my back.

821
01:45:48,200 --> 01:45:49,800
Give me your hand.

822
01:45:56,920 --> 01:45:59,120
- Have you got them?
- Yeah.

823
01:46:17,440 --> 01:46:19,280
Get buckled in!

824
01:46:37,520 --> 01:46:39,320
She'll be fine.

825
01:46:41,960 --> 01:46:43,280
I can't take off in this.

826
01:46:43,440 --> 01:46:47,240
- I'll point you in the right direction.
- Thank you.

827
01:47:44,080 --> 01:47:45,800
See anything familiar?

828
01:47:51,560 --> 01:47:53,880
I see an old man's sick joke.

829
01:47:54,360 --> 01:47:57,640
Really? Because I see
my new apartment...

830
01:47:57,800 --> 01:48:00,720
...and a place for Kitty,
one for my friends...

831
01:48:00,880 --> 01:48:03,720
...and that place over there, I'll rent out.

832
01:48:08,040 --> 01:48:12,080
But, you know, maybe you're right.
You know, maybe it is a little cold.

833
01:48:12,240 --> 01:48:16,040
It's... What's the word I'm searching for?
It's a little...

834
01:48:16,640 --> 01:48:18,280
...alien.

835
01:48:19,240 --> 01:48:22,920
It lacks that human touch.

836
01:48:25,760 --> 01:48:28,360
You have something that belongs to me.

837
01:48:45,160 --> 01:48:48,320
Metropolis Tower, this is seaplane
November-Seven-Two-Four-One-Hotel.

838
01:48:48,480 --> 01:48:50,000
Do you copy?

839
01:48:50,800 --> 01:48:54,160
Metropolis Tower, this is seaplane
November-Seven-Two-Four-One-Hotel.

840
01:48:54,320 --> 01:48:56,560
Do you copy? Damn it!

841
01:48:56,720 --> 01:49:00,200
Metropolis Tower, this is seaplane
November-Seven-Two-Four-One-Hotel.

842
01:49:00,360 --> 01:49:02,120
Do you copy?

843
01:49:03,920 --> 01:49:06,480
Lois! Are you all right?

844
01:49:06,880 --> 01:49:10,120
Yeah. What happened?

845
01:49:11,200 --> 01:49:13,720
- Superman.
- Where is he?

846
01:49:15,160 --> 01:49:16,360
He went back.

847
01:49:18,880 --> 01:49:21,000
- Richard, we have to turn around.
- What? No.

848
01:49:21,160 --> 01:49:23,680
- We have to turn around!
- We barely made it out of there.

849
01:49:23,840 --> 01:49:26,320
- Now you want me to go back?
- Yes, please!

850
01:49:27,040 --> 01:49:28,800
He'll die.

851
01:49:31,680 --> 01:49:33,480
All right, hold on.

852
01:49:50,280 --> 01:49:52,040
Kryptonite.

853
01:49:56,960 --> 01:49:58,840
You're asking yourself, "How?"

854
01:50:00,560 --> 01:50:05,320
Didn't your dad ever teach you
to look before you leap?

855
01:50:09,200 --> 01:50:12,040
Crystals. They're amazing, aren't they?

856
01:50:12,200 --> 01:50:15,320
They inherit the traits
of the minerals around them...

857
01:50:15,480 --> 01:50:20,080
...kind of like a son
inheriting the traits of his father!

858
01:50:22,760 --> 01:50:27,560
You took away five years of my life,
I'm just returning the favor!

859
01:50:30,920 --> 01:50:33,840
I'm still Superman!

860
01:50:42,120 --> 01:50:45,400
Get up! Come on!

861
01:52:13,680 --> 01:52:15,600
Now, fly.

862
01:53:14,200 --> 01:53:17,040
So long, Superman.

863
01:53:19,400 --> 01:53:22,360
<i>Your leadership can stir others...</i>

864
01:53:22,520 --> 01:53:24,600
<i>...to their own capacities
for moral betterment.</i>

865
01:53:24,760 --> 01:53:27,600
<i>The human heart is still subject
to monstrous deceits.</i>

866
01:53:31,080 --> 01:53:33,840
<i>Our destruction could have been avoided.
At this very moment...</i>

867
01:53:34,000 --> 01:53:35,560
<i>...I could embrace you in my arms.</i>

868
01:53:35,720 --> 01:53:38,040
<i>Your help would be called for endlessly.
Remember me.</i>

869
01:53:38,200 --> 01:53:41,400
<i>Even for those tasks which human beings
could solve themselves.</i>

870
01:53:51,400 --> 01:53:54,120
<i>Remember me, Kal-El.</i>

871
01:53:54,280 --> 01:53:56,120
<i>Remember me.</i>

872
01:54:04,640 --> 01:54:06,320
Superman's down there.

873
01:54:07,280 --> 01:54:09,560
- You sure?
- Yeah.

874
01:54:19,600 --> 01:54:22,120
- Richard!
- Yeah, I saw him. Strap in.

875
01:54:49,680 --> 01:54:51,400
Lois!

876
01:54:52,680 --> 01:54:54,400
Don't move.

877
01:55:38,600 --> 01:55:40,560
Come on, come on, come on.

878
01:55:44,160 --> 01:55:45,800
Richard!

879
01:55:45,960 --> 01:55:47,280
I'm trying! It's too choppy!

880
01:55:56,040 --> 01:55:57,560
Oh, my God.

881
01:57:40,840 --> 01:57:42,760
How did you find me?

882
01:57:48,040 --> 01:57:49,600
Thank you.

883
01:58:03,960 --> 01:58:05,800
What are you doing?

884
01:58:08,840 --> 01:58:10,040
I have to go back.

885
01:58:12,640 --> 01:58:14,320
You're hurt!

886
01:58:24,360 --> 01:58:25,960
Goodbye, Lois.

887
01:59:33,480 --> 01:59:35,720
<i>The technology on Krypton,
Superman's home world...</i>

888
01:59:35,880 --> 01:59:38,120
<i>...was based on manipulating
the growth of crystals.</i>

889
01:59:38,280 --> 01:59:39,600
<i>Sounds like hocus-pocus to me.</i>

890
01:59:39,760 --> 01:59:43,440
<i>Well, naturally, to the primitive mind,
any sufficiently advanced technology...</i>

891
01:59:43,600 --> 01:59:45,480
<i>...would be indistinguishable from magic.</i>

892
01:59:45,640 --> 01:59:48,920
<i>But imagine: cities, vehicles, weapons...</i>

893
01:59:49,080 --> 01:59:51,480
<i>...entire continents, all grown.</i>

894
01:59:51,640 --> 01:59:53,320
Lex?

895
01:59:55,080 --> 01:59:58,080
Are billions of people really going to die?

896
02:00:04,320 --> 02:00:05,960
Yes.

897
02:00:32,200 --> 02:00:33,480
Lex, what's happening?

898
02:00:39,200 --> 02:00:40,760
Go, go, go. Get to the helicopter.

899
02:00:43,520 --> 02:00:45,800
Go! Out, out! Now!

900
02:00:48,840 --> 02:00:51,880
No, no, no, take nothing!
Take nothing! Go, go!

901
02:00:53,720 --> 02:00:55,240
Got it.

902
02:01:37,560 --> 02:01:39,080
Here.

903
02:02:02,000 --> 02:02:03,880
- What did you do?
- I'm sorry!

904
02:02:04,040 --> 02:02:05,560
No!

905
02:02:24,320 --> 02:02:27,760
- What did you do?
- I'm sorry!

906
02:06:17,520 --> 02:06:18,960
Watch it.

907
02:06:20,280 --> 02:06:22,400
- Clear a path.
- Clear the way.

908
02:06:22,920 --> 02:06:24,480
- Move!
- Trauma One.

909
02:06:25,800 --> 02:06:28,040
- Where we going?
- Trauma One. Here it is.

910
02:06:33,640 --> 02:06:35,280
Watch it!

911
02:06:42,800 --> 02:06:44,120
Got him!

912
02:06:47,640 --> 02:06:48,960
Okay, I think I got it.

913
02:06:53,360 --> 02:06:56,080
Penetrating side wound
to right part of lower back.

914
02:06:57,360 --> 02:06:58,480
No hemorrhage.

915
02:07:02,960 --> 02:07:04,240
Shock at 200.

916
02:07:04,400 --> 02:07:06,160
Is that enough? He's not human.

917
02:07:06,320 --> 02:07:07,920
All right, charge to three, 360.

918
02:07:08,080 --> 02:07:09,600
Clear!

919
02:07:39,000 --> 02:07:40,240
It's kind of morbid, Perry.

920
02:07:41,040 --> 02:07:43,400
Always be prepared.

921
02:07:45,680 --> 02:07:47,320
How is she?

922
02:08:06,040 --> 02:08:08,920
Thank you. Thanks, baby.

923
02:08:11,600 --> 02:08:12,800
- Lois?
- Yeah.

924
02:08:14,880 --> 02:08:16,720
We can leave whenever you're ready.

925
02:08:16,880 --> 02:08:18,400
I mean...

926
02:08:19,920 --> 02:08:21,840
...you don't have to be here.

927
02:08:23,000 --> 02:08:24,760
Where else would I be?

928
02:08:24,920 --> 02:08:28,320
<i>Police have surrounded the area in order
to control thousands of visitors...</i>

929
02:08:28,480 --> 02:08:30,320
<i>...who have arrived
to show their support.</i>

930
02:08:30,480 --> 02:08:32,200
<i>Many are carrying signs and banners...</i>

931
02:08:32,360 --> 02:08:33,720
I could drive.

932
02:08:33,880 --> 02:08:36,240
<i>- no official announcements
over the past few hours...</i>

933
02:08:36,400 --> 02:08:38,880
<i>...but unconfirmed reports
from inside tell us...</i>

934
02:08:39,040 --> 02:08:40,760
<i>...the Man of Steel lies in a coma...</i>

935
02:08:40,920 --> 02:08:45,280
<i>...his condition unchanged
since he was admitted late yesterday.</i>

936
02:08:50,240 --> 02:08:53,360
<i>- Doctors have been vigilant in their...
- Foreign exchange markets...</i>

937
02:08:53,800 --> 02:08:56,720
- Where are you going?
- To the hospital.

938
02:08:56,880 --> 02:08:59,640
I'd be careful down there, guys.
It's a madhouse.

939
02:09:08,960 --> 02:09:11,960
- So much for parking.
- Do you think I can get in?

940
02:09:12,680 --> 02:09:15,440
You're Lois Lane. They'll let you in.

941
02:09:16,360 --> 02:09:19,080
I wanna go with Mommy.

942
02:09:39,400 --> 02:09:41,000
Taxi.

943
02:09:41,160 --> 02:09:42,560
I'll be right here.

944
02:09:49,560 --> 02:09:51,600
Watch your head, okay? Here we go.

945
02:10:22,360 --> 02:10:24,240
This way, Miss Lane.

946
02:10:45,520 --> 02:10:48,400
Mommy? Is he gonna get better?

947
02:10:50,360 --> 02:10:52,880
- I don't know.
- I want him to.

948
02:10:54,280 --> 02:10:56,400
I like him.

949
02:10:59,000 --> 02:11:00,600
Me too.

950
02:11:30,480 --> 02:11:33,160
I don't know if you can hear me.

951
02:11:35,680 --> 02:11:39,040
They say sometimes
that when people are...

952
02:11:41,920 --> 02:11:44,560
That sometimes they can hear you.

953
02:11:50,600 --> 02:11:52,760
I don't know if you can hear me.

954
02:12:01,360 --> 02:12:03,840
I wanted to tell you...

955
02:12:56,880 --> 02:12:58,720
Come on, honey.

956
02:13:40,640 --> 02:13:42,640
Step back, please!

957
02:13:59,120 --> 02:14:02,720
Lex, we only have six of those!

958
02:14:04,520 --> 02:14:05,760
Six?

959
02:14:09,400 --> 02:14:13,560
I would trade 300,000 coconuts...

960
02:14:13,720 --> 02:14:15,960
...and every ounce of your blood...

961
02:14:16,120 --> 02:14:20,560
...for a quart of gasoline!

962
02:14:21,280 --> 02:14:23,840
But what will we have to eat?

963
02:16:53,600 --> 02:16:55,560
You will be different.

964
02:16:59,080 --> 02:17:01,920
Sometimes, you will feel like an outcast.

965
02:17:03,040 --> 02:17:05,640
But you'll never be alone.

966
02:17:07,920 --> 02:17:10,480
You will make my strength your own.

967
02:17:13,320 --> 02:17:16,880
You will see my life through your eyes...

968
02:17:17,720 --> 02:17:22,880
...as your life will be seen through mine.

969
02:17:34,000 --> 02:17:37,880
The son becomes the father...

970
02:17:39,520 --> 02:17:44,080
...and the father becomes the son.

971
02:18:33,680 --> 02:18:35,440
Good night!

972
02:18:44,880 --> 02:18:46,240
I...

973
02:18:54,720 --> 02:18:56,600
Will we see you?

974
02:18:58,560 --> 02:19:00,160
Around?

975
02:19:02,560 --> 02:19:04,640
I'm always around.

976
02:19:09,480 --> 02:19:11,120
